                    <h2>Summary</h2>
                </div>
                
                <p>
                    End of Exile is a game in which the player is competing to pardon themselves from a national exile. In order to compete, however, they must first gain sponsorship from townspeople through casual conversation. Players quickly realize that they can collect sponsors faster by simply agreeing and abiding by the town’s beliefs. It isn’t until the ending scene, however, during a phone call with the player’s parents, that their own identity shift is realized.<br><br>
                    The reason I created End of Exile was to shine a light on the micro-decisions that many people make daily about whether to conform to ideals of success and community or stand by their own truth and risk social exile. This metaphor was best portrayed in a medium that people were already comfortable with; gaming. The metaphor was also aided by the use of VR which can quite literally put the player inside someone else’s shoes.


                </p>
            </div>
        
