            <div class="info-wrapper">
                <div class="info-text">
                    <h3>New Tech</h3>
                    <p>
                        Due to how new VR technology is to the open-source community, I found it difficult to troubleshoot some of the issues that arose. Specifically, during OVR development I saw many small issues pop up that few people in the community had seen. To get past this, I had to rely on the Oculus documentation rather than just reading forums. In addition to just knowing where to look, I had to practice a lot of patience throughout the project.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
    
            <div class="info-wrapper">
                <div class="info-text">
                    <h3>Broken Files</h3>
                    <p>
                        One of the most common recurring issues during dev, was broken files while transferring between engines (Maya, Substance, Unity). These files would either be incompatible or not formatted correctly. To solve this, I relied on my own documentation that I made any time I had a successful transfer since I knew I would be repeating that task later on. I also kept many backups and used source control which saved me a great deal after my computer crashed and corrupted my progress about halfway through the project. Luckily I had a day-old copy to jump off from.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
    
            <div class="info-wrapper">
                <div class="info-text">
                    <h3>Slow Renders</h3>
                    <p>
                        Since VR often struggles to render as quickly as other gaming platforms, I found myself unable to play one of my scenes without it crashing. Since I knew the root issue was the amount of 3d objects rendering, I used a reflection probe to capture a 3d image of those objects, then rendered that image onto a cube map and deleted the 3d objects. This meant the engine no longer needed to render 3d objects for my background and only needed to render a 2d cube map, optimizing the game greatly.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        

